[src:networking/osi-model] In the OSI reference model, the components of a communication system are distinguished in seven abstraction layers: Physical, Data Link, Network, Transport, Session, Presentation, and Application.
[src:networking/osi-model] The model describes communications from the physical implementation of transmitting bits across a transmission medium to the highest-level representation of data of a distributed application.
[src:networking/osi-model] Each layer has well-defined functions and semantics and serves a class of functionality to the layer above it and is served by the layer below it.
[src:networking/osi-model] Established, well-known communication protocols are decomposed in software development into the model's hierarchy of function calls.
[src:networking/osi-model] The Internet protocol suite as defined in RFC 1122 and RFC 1123 is a model of networking developed contemporarily to the OSI model, and was funded primarily by the U.S.
[src:networking/osi-model] It was the foundation for the development of the Internet.
[src:networking/osi-model] It assumed the presence of generic physical links and focused primarily on the software layers of communication, with a similar but much less rigorous structure than the OSI model.
[src:networking/osi-model] The model allows transparent communication through equivalent exchange of protocol data units (PDUs) between two parties, through what is known as peer-to-peer networking (also known as peer-to-peer communication).
[src:networking/osi-model] As a result, the OSI reference model has not only become an important piece among professionals and non-professionals alike, but also in all networking between one or many parties, due in large part to its commonly accepted user-friendly framework.
[src:networking/osi-model] The development of the OSI model started in the late 1970s to support the emergence of the diverse computer networking methods that were competing for application in the large national networking efforts in the world (see OSI protocols and Protocol Wars).
[src:networking/osi-model] In the 1980s, the model became a working product of the Open Systems Interconnection group at the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:networking/osi-model] While attempting to provide a comprehensive description of networking, the model failed to garner reliance during the design of the Internet, which is reflected in the less prescriptive Internet Protocol Suite, principally sponsored under the auspices of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:networking/osi-model] In the early- and mid-1970s, networking was largely either government-sponsored (NPL network in the UK, ARPANET in the US, CYCLADES in France) or vendor-developed with proprietary standards, such as IBM's Systems Network Architecture and Digital Equipment Corporation's DECnet.
[src:networking/osi-model] Public data networks were only just beginning to emerge, and these began to use the X.25 standard in the late 1970s.
[src:networking/osi-model] The Experimental Packet Switched System in the UK c.
[src:networking/osi-model] 1973–1975 identified the need for defining higher-level protocols.
[src:networking/osi-model] Beginning in 1977, the ISO initiated a program to develop general standards and methods of networking.
[src:networking/osi-model] A similar process evolved at the International Telegraph and Telephone Consultative Committee (CCITT, from French: *Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique*).
[src:networking/osi-model] Both bodies developed documents that defined similar networking models.
[src:networking/osi-model] The British Department of Trade and Industry acted as the secretariat, and universities in the United Kingdom developed prototypes of the standards.
[src:networking/osi-model] The OSI model was first defined in raw form in Washington, D.C., in February 1978 by French software engineer Hubert Zimmermann, and the refined but still draft standard was published by the ISO in 1980.
[src:networking/osi-model] The drafters of the reference model had to contend with many competing priorities and interests.
[src:networking/osi-model] The rate of technological change made it necessary to define standards that new systems could converge to rather than standardizing procedures after the fact; the reverse of the traditional approach to developing standards.
[src:networking/osi-model] Although not a standard itself, it was a framework in which future standards could be defined.
[src:networking/osi-model] In May 1983, the CCITT and ISO documents were merged to form *The Basic Reference Model for Open Systems Interconnection*, usually referred to as the *Open Systems Interconnection Reference Model*, *OSI Reference Model*, or simply *OSI model*.
[src:networking/osi-model] It was published in 1984 by both the ISO, as standard ISO 7498, and the renamed CCITT (now called the Telecommunications Standardization Sector of the International Telecommunication Union or ITU-T) as standard X.200.
[src:networking/osi-model] OSI had two major components: an abstract model of networking, called the Basic Reference Model or seven-layer model, and a set of specific protocols.
[src:networking/osi-model] The OSI reference model was a major advance in the standardisation of network concepts.
[src:networking/osi-model] It promoted the idea of a consistent model of protocol layers, defining interoperability between network devices and software.
[src:networking/osi-model] The concept of a seven-layer model was provided by the work of Charles Bachman at Honeywell Information Systems.
[src:networking/osi-model] Various aspects of OSI design evolved from experiences with the NPL network, ARPANET, CYCLADES, EIN, and the International Network Working Group (IFIP WG6.1).
[src:networking/osi-model] In this model, a networking system was divided into layers.
[src:networking/osi-model] Within each layer, one or more entities implement its functionality.
[src:networking/osi-model] Each entity interacted directly only with the layer immediately beneath it and provided facilities for use by the layer above it.
[src:networking/osi-model] The OSI standards documents are available from the ITU-T as the X.200 series of recommendations.
[src:networking/osi-model] Some of the protocol specifications were also available as part of the ITU-T X series.
[src:networking/osi-model] The equivalent ISO/IEC standards for the OSI model were available from ISO.
[src:networking/osi-model] OSI was an industry effort, attempting to get industry participants to agree on common network standards to provide multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:networking/osi-model] It was common for large networks to support multiple network protocol suites, with many devices unable to interoperate with other devices because of a lack of common protocols.
[src:networking/osi-model] For a period in the late 1980s and early 1990s, engineers, organizations and nations became polarized over the issue of which standard, the OSI model or the Internet protocol suite, would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:networking/osi-model] However, while OSI developed its networking standards in the late 1980s, TCP/IP came into widespread use on multi-vendor networks for internetworking.
[src:networking/osi-model] The OSI model is still used as a reference for teaching and documentation; however, the OSI protocols originally conceived for the model did not gain popularity.
[src:networking/osi-model] Some engineers argue the OSI reference model is still relevant to cloud computing.
[src:networking/osi-model] Others say the original OSI model does not fit today's networking protocols and have suggested instead a simplified approach.
[src:networking/osi-model] Communication protocols enable an entity in one host to interact with a corresponding entity at the same layer in another host.
[src:networking/osi-model] Service definitions, like the OSI model, abstractly describe the functionality provided to a layer *N* by a layer *N−1*, where *N* is one of the seven layers of protocols operating in the local host (with N=1 being the most basic layer, often represented at the bottom of a list).
[src:networking/osi-model] At each level *N*, two entities at the communicating devices (layer N *peers*) exchange protocol data units (PDUs) by means of a layer N *protocol*.
[src:networking/osi-model] Each PDU contains a payload, called the service data unit (SDU), along with protocol-related headers or footers.
[src:networking/osi-model] The *PDU* is passed to layer *N−1*, where it is known as the *service data unit* (*SDU*).
[src:networking/osi-model] At layer *N−1* the *SDU* is concatenated with a header, a footer, or both, producing a *layer N−1 PDU*.
[src:networking/osi-model] The process continues until reaching the lowermost level, from which the data is transmitted to the receiving device.
[src:networking/osi-model] At the receiving device the data is passed from the lowest to the highest layer as a series of *SDU*s while being successively stripped from each layer's header or footer until reaching the topmost layer, where the last of the data is consumed.
[src:networking/osi-model] ISO/IEC 7498-1 is also published as ITU-T Recommendation X.200.
[src:networking/osi-model] The recommendation X.200 describes seven layers, labelled 1 to 7.
[src:networking/osi-model] Layer 1 is the lowest layer in this model.
[src:networking/osi-model] The physical layer is responsible for the transmission and reception of unstructured raw data between a device, such as a network interface controller, Ethernet hub, or network switch, and a physical transmission medium.
[src:networking/osi-model] It converts the digital bits into electrical, radio, or optical signals (analogue signals).
[src:networking/osi-model] Layer specifications define characteristics such as voltage levels, the timing of voltage changes, physical data rates, maximum transmission distances, modulation scheme, channel access method and physical connectors.
[src:networking/osi-model] This includes the layout of pins, voltages, line impedance, cable specifications, signal timing and frequency for wireless devices.
[src:networking/osi-model] Bit rate control is done at the physical layer and may define transmission mode as simplex, half duplex, and full duplex.
[src:networking/osi-model] The components of a physical layer can be described in terms of the network topology.
[src:networking/osi-model] Physical layer specifications are included in the specifications for the ubiquitous Bluetooth, Ethernet, and USB standards.
[src:networking/osi-model] An example of a less well-known physical layer specification would be for the CAN standard.
[src:networking/osi-model] The physical layer also specifies how encoding occurs over a physical signal, such as electrical voltage or a light pulse.
[src:networking/osi-model] For example, a 1 bit might be represented on a copper wire by the transition from a 0-volt to a 5-volt signal, whereas a 0 bit might be represented by the transition from a 5-volt to a 0-volt signal.
[src:networking/osi-model] As a result, common problems occurring at the physical layer are often related to the incorrect media termination, EMI or noise scrambling, and NICs and hubs that are misconfigured or do not work correctly.
[src:networking/osi-model] The data link layer provides node-to-node data transfer—a link between two directly connected nodes.
[src:networking/osi-model] It detects and possibly corrects errors that may occur in the physical layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] It defines the protocol to establish and terminate a connection between two physically connected devices.
[src:networking/osi-model] It also defines the protocol for flow control between them.
[src:networking/osi-model] The MAC and LLC layers of IEEE 802 networks such as 802.3 Ethernet, 802.11 Wi-Fi, and 802.15.4 Zigbee operate at the data link layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] The Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) is a data link layer protocol that can operate over several different physical layers, such as synchronous and asynchronous serial lines.
[src:networking/osi-model] The ITU-T G.hn standard, which provides high-speed local area networking over existing wires (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables), includes a complete data link layer that provides both error correction and flow control by means of a selective-repeat sliding-window protocol.
[src:networking/osi-model] Security, specifically (authenticated) encryption, at this layer can be applied with MACsec.
[src:networking/osi-model] The network layer provides the functional and procedural means of transferring packets from one node to another connected in "different networks".
[src:networking/osi-model] It may, but does not need to, report delivery errors.
[src:networking/osi-model] Message delivery at the network layer is not necessarily guaranteed to be reliable; a network layer protocol may provide reliable message delivery, but it does not need to do so.
[src:networking/osi-model] A number of layer-management protocols, a function defined in the *management annex*, ISO 7498/4, belong to the network layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] These include routing protocols, multicast group management, network-layer information and error, and network-layer address assignment.
[src:networking/osi-model] It is the function of the payload that makes these belong to the network layer, not the protocol that carries them.
[src:networking/osi-model] Security, specifically (authenticated) encryption, at this layer can be applied with IPsec.
[src:networking/osi-model] The transport layer provides the functional and procedural means of transferring variable-length data sequences from a source host to a destination host from one application to another across a network while maintaining the quality-of-service functions.
[src:networking/osi-model] Transport protocols may be connection-oriented or connectionless.
[src:networking/osi-model] The amount of data in a data segment must be small enough to allow for a network-layer header and a transport-layer header.
[src:networking/osi-model] For example, for data being transferred across Ethernet, the MTU is 1500 bytes, the minimum size of a TCP header is 20 bytes, and the minimum size of an IPv4 header is 20 bytes, so the maximum segment size is 1500−(20+20) bytes, or 1460 bytes.
[src:networking/osi-model] The process of dividing data into segments is called segmentation; it is an optional function of the transport layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] The transport layer also controls the reliability of a given link between a source and destination host through flow control, error control, and acknowledgments of sequence and existence.
[src:networking/osi-model] Some protocols are state- and connection-oriented.
[src:networking/osi-model] This means that the transport layer can keep track of the segments and retransmit those that fail delivery through the acknowledgment hand-shake system.
[src:networking/osi-model] The transport layer will also provide the acknowledgement of the successful data transmission and sends the next data if no errors occurred.
[src:networking/osi-model] Reliability, however, is not a strict requirement within the transport layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] Protocols like UDP, for example, are used in applications that are willing to accept some packet loss, reordering, errors or duplication.
[src:networking/osi-model] Streaming media, real-time multiplayer games and voice over IP (VoIP) are examples of applications in which loss of packets is not usually a fatal problem.
[src:networking/osi-model] The OSI connection-oriented transport protocol defines five classes of connection-mode transport protocols, ranging from class 0 (which is also known as TP0 and provides the fewest features) to class 4 (TP4, designed for less reliable networks, similar to the Internet).
[src:networking/osi-model] Class 0 contains no error recovery and was designed for use on network layers that provide error-free connections.
[src:networking/osi-model] Class 4 is closest to TCP, although TCP contains functions, such as the graceful close, which OSI assigns to the session layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] Also, all OSI TP connection-mode protocol classes provide expedited data and preservation of record boundaries.
[src:networking/osi-model] An easy way to visualize the transport layer is to compare it with a post office, which deals with the dispatch and classification of mail and parcels sent.
[src:networking/osi-model] A post office inspects only the outer envelope of mail to determine its delivery.
[src:networking/osi-model] Higher layers may have the equivalent of double envelopes, such as cryptographic presentation services that can be read by the addressee only.
[src:networking/osi-model] Roughly speaking, tunnelling protocols operate at the transport layer, such as carrying non-IP protocols such as IBM's SNA or Novell's IPX over an IP network, or end-to-end encryption with IPsec.
[src:networking/osi-model] L2TP carries PPP frames inside transport segments.
[src:networking/osi-model] Although not developed under the OSI Reference Model and not strictly conforming to the OSI definition of the transport layer, the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) of the Internet Protocol Suite are commonly categorized as layer 4 protocols within OSI.
[src:networking/osi-model] Transport Layer Security (TLS) does not strictly fit inside the model either.
[src:networking/osi-model] It contains characteristics of the transport and presentation layers.
[src:networking/osi-model] The session layer creates the setup, controls the connections, and ends the teardown, between two or more computers, which is called a "session".
[src:networking/osi-model] Common functions of the session layer include user logon (establishment) and user logoff (termination) functions.
[src:networking/osi-model] Including this matter, authentication methods are also built into most client software, such as FTP Client and NFS Client for Microsoft Networks.
[src:networking/osi-model] Therefore, the session layer establishes, manages and terminates the connections between the local and remote applications.
[src:networking/osi-model] The session layer also provides for full-duplex, half-duplex, or simplex operation, and establishes procedures for checkpointing, suspending, restarting, and terminating a session between two related streams of data, such as an audio and a video stream in a web-conferencing application.
[src:networking/osi-model] Therefore, the session layer is commonly implemented explicitly in application environments that use remote procedure calls.
[src:networking/osi-model] For this very reason, outgoing messages during encapsulation are converted into a format specified by the application layer, while the conversion for incoming messages during deencapsulation are reversed.
[src:networking/osi-model] The presentation layer handles protocol conversion, data encryption, data decryption, data compression, data decompression, incompatibility of data representation between operating systems, and graphic commands.
[src:networking/osi-model] The presentation layer transforms data into the form that the application layer accepts, to be sent across a network.
[src:networking/osi-model] Since the presentation layer converts data and graphics into a display format for the application layer, the presentation layer is sometimes called the syntax layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] Such application programs fall outside the scope of the OSI model unless they are directly integrated into the application layer through the functions of communication, as is the case with applications such as web browsers and email programs.
[src:networking/osi-model] Other examples of software are Microsoft Network Software for File and Printer Sharing and Unix/Linux Network File System Client for access to shared file resources.
[src:networking/osi-model] Application-layer functions typically include file sharing, message handling, and database access, through the most common protocols at the application layer, known as HTTP, FTP, SMB/CIFS, TFTP, and SMTP.
[src:networking/osi-model] When identifying communication partners, the application layer determines the identity and availability of communication partners for an application with data to transmit.
[src:networking/osi-model] The most important distinction in the application layer is the distinction between the application entity and the application.
[src:networking/osi-model] For example, a reservation website might have two application entities: one using HTTP to communicate with its users, and one for a remote database protocol to record reservations.
[src:networking/osi-model] Neither of these protocols have anything to do with reservations.
[src:networking/osi-model] That logic is in the application itself.
[src:networking/osi-model] The application layer has no means to determine the availability of resources in the network.
[src:networking/osi-model] Cross-layer functions are services that are not tied to a given layer, but may affect more than one layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] Some orthogonal aspects, such as management and security, involve all of the layers (See ITU-T X.800 Recommendation).
[src:networking/osi-model] These services are aimed at improving the CIA triad—confidentiality, integrity, and availability—of the transmitted data.
[src:networking/osi-model] Cross-layer functions are the norm, in practice, because the availability of a communication service is determined by the interaction between network design and network management protocols.
[src:networking/osi-model] Neither the OSI Reference Model, nor any OSI protocol specifications, outline any programming interfaces, other than deliberately abstract service descriptions.
[src:networking/osi-model] Protocol specifications define a methodology for communication between peers, but the software interfaces are implementation-specific.
[src:networking/osi-model] For example, the Network Driver Interface Specification (NDIS) and Open Data-Link Interface (ODI) are interfaces between the media (layer 2) and the network protocol (layer 3).
[src:networking/osi-model] The table below presents a list of OSI layers, the original OSI protocols, and some *approximate* modern matches.
[src:networking/osi-model] This correspondence is rough: the OSI model contains idiosyncrasies not found in later systems such as the IP stack in modern Internet.
[src:networking/osi-model] The design of protocols in the TCP/IP model of the Internet does not concern itself with strict hierarchical encapsulation and layering.
[src:networking/osi-model] RFC 3439 contains a section entitled "Layering considered harmful".
[src:networking/osi-model] TCP/IP does recognize four broad layers of functionality which are derived from the operating scope of their contained protocols: the scope of the software application; the host-to-host transport path; the internetworking range; and the scope of the direct links to other nodes on the local network.
[src:networking/osi-model] These comparisons are based on the original seven-layer protocol model as defined in ISO 7498, rather than refinements in the internal organization of the network layer.
[src:networking/osi-model] The OSI protocol suite that was specified as part of the OSI project was considered by many as too complicated and inefficient, and to a large extent unimplementable.
[src:networking/osi-model] Taking the "forklift upgrade" approach to networking, it specified eliminating all existing networking protocols and replacing them at all layers of the stack.
[src:networking/osi-model] This made implementation difficult and was resisted by many vendors and users with significant investments in other network technologies.
[src:networking/osi-model] In addition, the protocols included so many optional features that many vendors' implementations were not interoperable.
[src:networking/osi-model] Although the OSI model is often still referenced, the Internet protocol suite has become the standard for networking.
[src:networking/osi-model] TCP/IP's pragmatic approach to computer networking and to independent implementations of simplified protocols made it a practical methodology.
[src:networking/osi-model] Some protocols and specifications in the OSI stack remain in use, one example being IS-IS, which was specified for OSI as ISO/IEC 10589:2002 and adapted for Internet use with TCP/IP as RFC 1142.
